##The editor of the Lancet railed against the British government's failure to follow science, ignoring important evidence from China and Italy. "The government is playing roulette with the public. "

With the outbreak of new crown disease in many countries in Europe, governments have to prevent and control the spread of the epidemic response measures. After the third emergency cabinet meeting of the Boris Johnson, the Prime Minister issued a statement on the spread of the new coronavirus: The UK officially enters phase II of the prevention of the epidemic, as a delay.

Previously, the rapid rise in the number of infections in the UK was due to a sharp deterioration in the state of the epidemic in Italy and an increase in imported cases from the UK. Therefore, the British government published a complete epidemic prevention plan to deal with the spread of the epidemic, specific measures include four stages: containment, delay, research and impairment. From the moment Boris announced the second phase of the "delay" , it was clear that the epidemic in the UK was on the verge of further deterioration, widespread community transmission and the need for "social isolation" to be considered.

There are now 10 deaths in the UK from NCP, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 596, an increase of 140 from 456 the day before. Boris said at the press conference that schools would not be closed for the time being, although the second phase of the epidemic was expected to involve "social isolation" , "according to scientific advice, stopping classes does more harm than good, " he said, but said schools would be banned from allowing students to travel abroad, while advising people over 70 and those with pre-existing health problems to avoid travel in the near future.

Starting March 13, anyone with new symptoms of pneumonia, such as cough and fever, must be quarantined at home for seven days. If symptoms do not improve or worsen after 7 days, call for medical help. In addition, the British government will change the new crown disease detection rules, the detection will focus on the more severe symptoms of patients, for only mild symptoms recommended home isolation.

British Prime Minister Boris Johnson speaks at a press conference

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
As early as March 10, richard Holden, editor in chief of the Lancet, the world's leading medical journal, and a fellow at the Royal College of Physicians and the Academy of Medical Sciences, took to social media to deplore the British government's decision not to act sooner to "delay" the spread of the disease, "This may be understandable, but it is a mistake, " he said. "As one British epidemiologist told me, their decision is so disappointing that the UK should have taken more aggressive social distancing measures immediately. "

"The British government, as if Hancock (Matt Hancock, Health Secretary) and Boris Johnson, claimed they were following science. But that is not the case, and there is clear evidence that we need to urgently implement social segregation and corresponding closures. Right now, the government is playing roulette with the public, and that's a big mistake,"Richard Holden said.

After Boris's statement on the latest phase of the epidemic was released on March 12, Richard Holden posted a series of nine messages on social media expressing his dissatisfaction and attitude towards the new phase of the epidemic.

The first of Richard Holden's nine tweets (Source: Twitter)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
First, the statement that "our response to the new coronavirus is an evidence-based assessment of what is happening in the UK" , "This is another big mistake, " Richard says. Britain's response needs to draw lessons from the experiences of China and Italy, not just from what is happening in Britain. It is simply incredible that the government seems to ignore the most important evidence from elsewhere."

Later, Richard Holden linked to a paper in the Lancet entitled "New Coronaviruses and Italy: What's next, " and said it was why, in the light of what happened in Italy, about the complacency of the British government. "Last Sunday, some Italian writers called me to explain the urgent, tragic and worrying situation they documented in this article, " he said.

Image | screenshot from The Lancet paper on The Italian epidemic, published March 12(Source: The Lancet)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On COVID-19, Richard Holden said he did not mean to sound alarmist. "But if you look at the Italian experience, there are some important lessons here. The British government either didn't realize it or ignored it, " he said, "Even if the Italian government had made such a brave decision and acted accordingly, it would not have been able to deal with the epidemic in practice. "

"The capacity of the Italian health system may not be sufficient to cope with the exponential growth in the demand for intensive care beds, " he said, "The UK is in fact similar to Italy, " he said. At the current rate of growth in Italy, Italy will have the largest number of intensive care beds by March 14. To make matters worse, the number of patients in intensive care will not stop growing. Without urgent action, the situation in Italy could become "uncontrollable" and "catastrophic" as the number of seriously ill patients continues to rise.

To avoid a "catastrophe out of control" in the UK, Richard Calls for "honesty about what may happen in the next few weeks" and says the UK needs to urgently increase its intensive care capacity, the NHS is not yet ready. "I went to a hospital today [ March 12] and they've got 19 new CAP patients in the hospital's Intensive Care Unit (Itu) . "

He advised people to read this sentence carefully in the latest issue of Italian newspapers, think again -- "intensive care specialists are already thinking about denying life-saving services to the most severely ill patients and prioritizing those who are most likely to survive when deciding who to give suction to. " "please calm down, it's not about killing anyone, it's about being forced to make decisions that will bother them, " one user wrote in response. The system is not at all suited to managing patients and is based on wartime criteria of mass casualty. It's not ageism, it's not discrimination of any kind, it's just a choice made with limited resources."

But it seems to have provoked Richard Holden, he went on to post: "again, I'm not being alarmist. What is happening in Italy is real, and it is happening. Our government [ in the UK ] has not prepared people for this reality. We need immediate and decisive social isolation and closure, and we need the NHS to be ready. This is a very serious request."

Figure | one of 9 tweets: again, not alarmist (Source: Twitter)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In conclusion, Richard Holden said: The UK is on the brink of an avoidable disaster. "In addition to more aggressive government action to control the epidemic and prevent deaths, health care workers will also bear the brunt of government complacency, " he stressed, "In Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. [ the worst affected region in Italy ] , 20 per cent of health-care workers have been infected and some have died. "

BBC News also said in its report on what the UK's second phase of "procrastination" represented, "The COVID-19 is spreading in the UK and there is expected to be a pandemic. In the worst case, 80 percent of the population will be infected if nothing is done."On the question of whether schools will be closed and whether public meetings will be banned, the government is likely to take steps in the future including suspending classes (but needing new legislation or a shortage of teachers) , restricting the use of public transport, stopping large gatherings, and supporting the emergency services, measures such as keeping the police focused on the most serious crimes and maintaining public order.

However, the BBC also said: "Other countries such as Italy have taken some of these measures, but often because they have more cases. " In addition, some British officials have expressed concern about the effect of the measures. For example, while closing schools can reduce the gathering of people, it will force parents to stay at home. That's GONNA be a problem. This could lead to a reduction in the number of available health care workers, or involve high risk groups such as grandparents at greater risk.

The interpretation of the British government's decision, published by Bloomberg News, is even more incisive, "The strategy announced by the government of the Boris Johnson is to slow the spread of the virus, but it is not fully contained, " he said. Then most people get infected, some of them feel sick, but almost all of them recover. Then, if a sufficient percentage of the population has already had the disease, the country will be immunized."

Photo | Bloomberg News Screenshot (via Bloomberg)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Earlier, DeepTech interviewed epidemiologist and tenured professor Chen Zhengming of Oxford University, "Some of the measures implemented in China are feasible in the UK, but some are not feasible and the social costs are too high, " he has said. With the exception of London, the UK has a relatively low population density, which is relatively good for disease control and Prevention. At the same time, communities in the UK are open and not fenced in, so they can not be managed as close as in China. In addition, the public may not agree."

As for the future of the disease in the UK, the Boris Johnson said in a statement: "The UK is in the situation in Italy four weeks ago. " It is hoped that after authoritative scientists, including the chief editor of The Lancet, have spoken, would make the UK more cautious and proactive in its response to the outbreak, to avoid a future like Italy's. The suspension will be discussed by the FA on March 13, with the manager of Arsenal, the Premier League's most established club, being diagnosed with new champions pneumonia, and with other players suffering from the symptoms of the epidemic being quarantined.

The impact of the outbreak on the UK is slowly being felt everywhere, and it is hoped that the risks of the outbreak can be addressed, avoid what Boris calls a "lock-in" : "For many families, they may face the prospect of a life-and-death separation. "
